The policy uses factored action heads: instead of outputting probabilities over all possible moves (which would be thousands), it predicts a from-square distribution and a to-square distribution independently. The score for a move is the sum of the from-square log-probability and the to-square log-probability. This factorization keeps the output layer small (128 outputs instead of 4,096+).


Advantage Estimation (GAE)
GAE computes advantages by looking at multi-step returns with exponential weighting:
\[
\hat{A}_t = \sum_{l=0}^{T-t} (\gamma \lambda)^l \delta_{t+l}
\]
where \(\delta_t = r_t + \gamma V(s_{t+1}) - V(s_t)\) is the TD error.
The hyperparameters: \(\gamma = 0.99\) (discount factor), \(\lambda = 0.95\) (GAE smoothing). These control the bias-variance tradeoff in advantage estimation — higher \(\lambda\) gives lower bias but higher variance.


Training Loop
Each training episode:

Rollout: play a full game via self-play, recording states, actions, log-probabilities, rewards, and value estimates at each step
Compute returns and advantages: walk backward through the trajectory using GAE
Policy loss: \(-\frac{1}{T} \sum_t \log \pi(a_t | s_t) \cdot \hat{A}_t\) — nudge the policy toward moves with positive advantage
Value loss: \(\frac{1}{T} \sum_t (V(s_t) - R_t)^2\) — improve value function predictions
Backward pass: compute gradients through the entire network via autodiff
Adam update: update all 45,873 parameters







A2C update step in CJC-Lang





fn a2c_update_adam(params: Any, trajectory: Any, config: Any,
                   adam_state: Any, step: i64) -&gt; Any {
    let advantages = compute_gae(trajectory, config);
    advantages = whiten(advantages);

    let policy_loss = 0.0;
    let value_loss = 0.0;
    let t = 0;
    while t &lt; len(trajectory) {
        policy_loss = policy_loss - trajectory[t].log_prob * advantages[t];
        let val_err = trajectory[t].value - trajectory[t].return_;
        value_loss = value_loss + val_err * val_err;
        t = t + 1;
    }
    policy_loss = policy_loss / float(len(trajectory));
    value_loss = value_loss / float(len(trajectory));

    let total_loss = policy_loss + 0.5 * value_loss;

    // Backward pass through autodiff
    grad_graph.zero_grad();
    grad_graph.backward(total_loss);

    // Adam optimizer update for each parameter tensor
    let p = 0;
    while p &lt; len(params) {
        let grad = grad_graph.grad(params[p].idx);
        params[p] = adam_step(params[p], grad, adam_state[p], step,
                              config.lr, 0.9, 0.999, 1e-8);
        p = p + 1;
    }
    params
}



Additional training features:

Temperature annealing (1.2 → 0.8): starts with high exploration, gradually becomes more greedy
Advantage whitening: normalizes advantages to zero mean and unit variance for stable gradients
Resignation threshold: the agent can resign when its value estimate drops below a threshold, saving compute on hopeless games
Move-count penalty: small penalty per ply (0.001) to discourage aimless play

What’s in the Box

A Complete Language
CJC-Lang is a statically-aware, dynamically-typed language with a syntax that should feel familiar if you’ve written Rust, Python, or R:
fn fibonacci(n: i64) -&gt; i64 {
    if n &lt;= 1 {
        return n;
    }
    return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}

print(fibonacci(30));
The language supports:

Functions with required type annotations and optional default parameters
Closures with automatic capture analysis
Control flow: if/else, while, for..in, pattern matching with match
Data types: structs, enums, traits, generics
25+ value types at runtime: integers, floats, strings, arrays, tensors, DataFrames, maps, sets, complex numbers, sparse matrices, and more



Two Execution Engines
Every CJC-Lang program can run on two independent engines:

cjc-eval — an AST tree-walk interpreter. Fast startup, great for scripting and the REPL.
cjc-mir-exec — a MIR register-machine executor with an optimization pipeline: constant folding, strength reduction, dead code elimination, common subexpression elimination, and loop-invariant code motion.

cjcl run program.cjcl            # AST interpreter (default)
cjcl run program.cjcl --mir-opt  # MIR executor with optimizations
Both engines are tested for parity — given the same input and seed, they produce identical output. This dual-engine architecture catches bugs that a single implementation would miss.


282+ Built-in Functions
CJC-Lang ships with a broad standard library, all implemented from scratch:
Math & Trig: sin, cos, sqrt, pow, log, exp, abs, floor, ceil, round, hypot, atan2, and more
Statistics: mean, median, variance, sd, quantile, cor, cov, t_test, chi_squared_test, anova_oneway, logistic_regression
Linear Algebra: matmul, det, solve, eigh, lstsq, linalg.lu, linalg.qr, linalg.cholesky, linalg.inv, kron, norm
Tensors: Tensor.zeros, Tensor.randn, Tensor.from_vec, sigmoid, tanh_activation, leaky_relu, batch_norm, dropout_mask, one_hot
DataFrames (tidyverse-style): read_csv, filter, select, mutate, group_by, summarize, join, arrange, window_mean
Strings: str_detect, str_replace_all, str_extract, str_split, str_to_upper, str_trim
Signal Processing: rfft, psd, hann, hamming, blackman, fft_2d
I/O: read_csv, write_csv, file_read, file_write, json_parse, json_stringify
Automatic Differentiation: GradGraph.new, grad_checkpoint, clip_grad, stop_gradient, forward-mode dual numbers and reverse-mode tape
let data: Any = read_csv("measurements.csv");
let filtered: Any = filter(data, col("temperature") &gt; 20.0);
let grouped: Any = group_by(filtered, "city");
let result: Any = summarize(grouped, tidy_mean(col("temperature")));
print(result);


Determinism as a Contract
This is the core principle. CJC-Lang enforces determinism at every layer:

RNG: SplitMix64 with explicit seed threading. No OS entropy, no thread-local state.
Floating-point reductions: Kahan compensated summation and binned accumulators. sum([0.1, 0.2, 0.3]) gives the same bits whether you process forward, backward, or in parallel chunks.
Collections: BTreeMap and BTreeSet everywhere. Not a single HashMap in the codebase. Zero iteration-order non-determinism.
SIMD: Tensor kernels use SIMD acceleration but avoid fused multiply-add (FMA) to guarantee cross-platform bit-identical results.
NoGC verification: A static pass that proves certain code paths never allocate on the GC heap.

// Run the same computation twice with the same seed — identical output guaranteed
cjcl run simulation.cjcl --seed 42
cjcl run simulation.cjcl --seed 42  // bit-for-bit identical


The Compiler Pipeline
CJC-Lang isn’t just an interpreter — it’s a full compiler pipeline:
Source → Lexer → Parser → AST → HIR → MIR → Optimize → Execute

Lexer: Hand-written tokenizer with full Unicode support
Parser: Pratt (top-down operator precedence) parser with error recovery at declaration boundaries
HIR: High-level IR with capture analysis for closures
MIR: Mid-level IR with CFG construction, SSA form (Cytron’s algorithm), dominator trees (Cooper-Harvey-Kennedy), loop analysis, and reduction classification
Optimizer: Six-pass pipeline — constant folding, strength reduction, DCE, CSE, LICM, then constant folding again
Escape Analysis: Four-phase analysis that classifies values into Stack, Arena, or Rc tiers automatically



Real-World Examples — No Libraries, No Imports, No Dependencies
Everything below runs on cjcl alone. No pip install, no npm, no linking against BLAS or LAPACK. Every tensor operation, every activation function, every optimizer, every statistical test — implemented from scratch inside CJC-Lang’s runtime.
Each example demonstrates a specific capability. I’ll show the code, the actual terminal output, and explain what it proves about the language.


1. Transformer Forward Pass — Multi-Head Attention, KV-Cache, LayerNorm
This is the most complex single example. A complete transformer block: pre-norm architecture with multi-head self-attention, GELU feed-forward network, residual connections, and a KV-cache for efficient inference.
// Model: 8-dim embeddings, 2 attention heads, 16-dim FFN
let x = Tensor.from_vec(input_data, [1, 4, 8]);

// Q/K/V projection weights [model_dim, model_dim]
let Wq = Tensor.from_vec(wq_data, [8, 8]);
let Wk = Tensor.from_vec(wk_data, [8, 8]);
let Wv = Tensor.from_vec(wv_data, [8, 8]);
let Wo = Tensor.from_vec(wo_data, [8, 8]);

// LayerNorm parameters
let gamma = Tensor.ones([8]);
let beta  = Tensor.zeros([8]);

// KV-Cache for autoregressive generation
let kv_k = Scratchpad.new(32, 8);
let kv_v = Scratchpad.new(32, 8);

// ─── Forward Pass ───

// Step 1: Pre-norm
let x_norm = x.layer_norm(gamma, beta);

// Step 2: Q/K/V projections
let Q = x_norm.linear(Wq, bias_zero);
let K = x_norm.linear(Wk, bias_zero);
let V = x_norm.linear(Wv, bias_zero);

// Step 3: Populate KV-Cache
kv_k.append(K.view_reshape([4, 8]));
kv_v.append(V.view_reshape([4, 8]));

// Step 4: Multi-head attention
let Q_heads = Q.split_heads(2);       // [1,4,8] → [1,2,4,4]
let K_heads = K.split_heads(2);
let V_heads = V.split_heads(2);
let attn_out = attention(Q_heads, K_heads, V_heads);
let attn_merged = attn_out.merge_heads();  // [1,2,4,4] → [1,4,8]
let attn_proj = attn_merged.linear(Wo, bias_zero);

// Step 5: Residual + FFN
let x2 = x + attn_proj;
let x2_norm = x2.layer_norm(gamma, beta);
let ff_hidden = x2_norm.linear(W_ff1, bias_ff1);
let ff_act = ff_hidden.gelu();
let ff_out = ff_act.linear(W_ff2, bias_ff2);
let output = x2 + ff_out;

// Step 6: Determinism verification — run it AGAIN
// ... (identical forward pass) ...
assert_eq(val, val2);
print("PASS: Transformer forward pass — deterministic, zero-GC");
$ cjcl run examples/transformer_forward.cjcl
1. LayerNorm shape: [1, 4, 8]
2. Q shape: [1, 4, 8] K shape: [1, 4, 8] V shape: [1, 4, 8]
3. KV-Cache K len: 4 V len: 4
4. Q_heads shape: [1, 2, 4, 4]
5. Attention output shape: [1, 2, 4, 4]
6. Merged heads shape: [1, 4, 8]
