6. Physics-Informed Neural Network (PINN) — Solving PDEs
A neural network that learns the solution to a partial differential equation by embedding physics directly into the loss function. This PINN solves the 1D harmonic oscillator u’’ + u = 0, discovering sin(x) from boundary conditions alone.
// PDE: u_xx + u = 0 on [0, π]
// Boundary conditions: u(0) = 0, u(π) = 0
// Exact solution: u(x) = sin(x)

// Network: MLP [1 → 16 → 16 → 1], tanh activations
// Total parameters: (1×16 + 16) + (16×16 + 16) + (16×1 + 1) = 321

// Loss has three components:
//   1. Data loss: MSE between network output and known data points
//   2. Physics loss: MSE of PDE residual (u_xx + u) at collocation points
//   3. Boundary loss: u(0)² + u(π)²

// u_xx computed via central finite differences on the network:
//   u_xx(x) ≈ (u(x+ε) - 2u(x) + u(x-ε)) / ε²

// Optimizer: Adam (β1=0.9, β2=0.999)
// Trained for 500 epochs
