Every example below comes from real files in the repository — demo programs, test fixtures, or integration tests.

Closures and Higher-Order Functions
CJC-Lang supports lambda expressions with capture analysis. The compiler performs lambda lifting during HIR lowering, converting closures into top-level functions with explicit environment parameters:

Lambda with capture, passed as higher-order function

fn apply(f: fn(i64) -&gt; i64, x: i64) -&gt; i64 {
    f(x)
}

fn main() -&gt; i64 {
    let double = |x: i64| x * 2;
    let result: i64 = apply(double, 21);
    print(f"result: {result}");
    result
}
The capture analysis feeds into the NoGC verifier — if a closure captures a reference that would require GC, the verifier flags it.


